table.description: <font color="#99cc00">Each record in the MN-R_Carto_Land_UC table gets a new sequence number. The landcover/use features with lowest sequence number are less important to display then features with a higher sequence number. The sequence number is according to the “Display order of Landcover/use features” list below. Landcover/use features that are not in the list, are added to the table before the Landcover/use features that are in the list. (because they cannot overlap, or are unimportant). So the ‘unordered’ landcover/use features will have a lower sequence number then the ‘ordered’ landcover/use features. It is the purpose of the MN-R_Carto_Land_UC table that areas are drawn on top of each other, beginning with area with sequence number 1 and so on. So as latest, the most important areas are drawn and will be most visible.</font> <font color="#99cc00"> </font>Display order of Landcover/use features : Order Feature Code Feature Name 1 7110 Building 2 9776 Airport Runway 3 9732 Airport Ground 4 9790 Shopping Ground 5 9789 Military Ground 6 9788 Cemetery 7 9768 Stadium 8 9780 Institution 9 9771 University 10 9756 Parking Area 11 9744 Golf Course 12 9733 Amusement Park Ground 13 9748 Hospital Ground 14 9720 Industrial Harbour Area 15 9715 Industrial Area 16 9353 Company Ground 17 7180 Island 18 7170 Park 19 9710 Beach, Dune and Plain Sand 20 7120 Forest (Woodland) 21 9725 Moors & Heathland 22 9787 Other Land Use

One of the Official Names is delivered in the Freeway Interection table. The full information about the names is in the Freeway Intersection Name tables.
table.name: MNR_Freeway_Inters

table.description:
The Grade Seperated Crossing table contains the composition of the Grade Seperated Crossing (GSC). GSC can be composed of :  
  • Road Element, Ferry Element, Address Area Boundary Element (table Network Route Link)
  • Railway Element (table Railway)
  • Network Junction and Railway Junction (table Junction)
  • Water Element (line) and Water Element (area) (table Cartographic Water Line and table Cartographic Water Area)
Feature ID field can link to an each table that contains one of the composing features. Feature Type field indicates the type of composing feature (and to which table the Feature ID field is linked). For each of the composing features, also the Z-level is provided in the Grade Seperate Crossing table.
table.name: MNR_GSC

table.description: The Hierarchical Index Name Relationships is a link table between an hierarchical index feature in Hierarchical Index table and a name set in Locality Name Set and Locality Name Set Name table. Additionaly the name type is indicated.
table.name: MNR_HierIndex_Name_Rel

table.description:
The Hierarchical Index table contains index relevant area features. Only the Order 1 Area to Order 9 Area and Order 1 Index Area to Order 10 Index Area features fit in an hierarchical structure. The other areas might be overlapping or order 8/9 crossing. Only the the lowest orders and the non-hierarchical areas have a link to the Network Route Link. . Compared to the indexing based on localities :
  • Indexing Hierarchical : no merging of equally named index relevant features.
  • Indexing Hierarchical : no adornment setting
  • Indexing Hierarchical : no priority setting
  • Indexing Hierarchical : no discriminator setting
  • Indexing Hierarchical : no link to Anchor Points or City Center
  • Indexing Hierarchical : only index relevant AREA features
  • Indexing Hierarchical : additional names : country, order 1 to order 7
  • Indexing Locality : 1 locality = 1 nameset , locality linked to network names
  • Indexing Hierarchical : 1 index relevant feature with multiple nameset, index relevant fetaure linked to network names.
table.name: MNR_Hierarchical_Index

table.description: Intersections table contains all Intersection. Also one of the official names is included in the Intersections table. The full information about Intersection names can be found in the Intersection Names tables. The composition of the Intersection can be found in the Intersection Index table. Intersections are the bounding features for a Level 2 Road (Level 2 Road table) and Freeway Intersections (Freeway Intersection table)
table.name: MNR_Inters

table.description: The Junction table contains the geometry and attributes of all the Junction for network features (Road Element, Ferry Element and Address Area Boundary Element) and for Railway Element.

Feature Type field indicates if Feature ID field links to Road Element or Intersection.
table.name: MNR_Level2R_Idx

table.description:
The Locality table contains the locality names in various notation alphabet and character encoding UTF-8.
Locality names can be sourced from different kind of features : an index relevant area feature name, an index relevant city center name or an index relevant anchor point address component name that is shared by multiple anchor points, postal code, ....
If the locality name is sourced from one or multiple area features, the road elements part of these area features are directly linked to the locality name. If the locality name is sourced from a city center, the city center feature is directly linked to the locality name. If the locality name is sourced from an anchor point address component, the anchor points are directly linked to the locality name. If the locality name is sourced from a postal code (or postal code name), the road elements of the postal district are directly linked to the locality name.
A locality name can be an official name or an alternate name.
table.name: MNR_Loc

table.description:
Maneuver table contains the geometry of the decision point (=Junction) of following maneuvers:
  • Bifurcation
  • Calculated Prohibited Maneuver
  • Image Maneuver
  • Prohibited Maneuver (type Prohibited Maneuver and type Implicit Turn)
  • Lane Connectivity
  • Priority Maneuver (= Through Route)
  • Restricted Maneuver
  • SignPost Information
table.name: MNR_Maneuver

table.description:
All maneuvers (Bifurcation, Calculated Prohibited Maneuver, Image Maneuver, Prohibited Maneuver, Lane Connectivity, Priority Maneuver, Restricted Maneuver, SignPost Information, Linear Assignment Maneuver) are represented with the maneuver path as a dissolved line feature (i.e. one line feature for the complete maneuver) with the orientation of the line in the maneuver from-to direction.
Bifurcations are split into the individual maneuver options with the same maneuver ID and a different maneuver sequence number per maneuver option. The sequence for the out-bounding paths is ordered left to right. First out-bounding path starts at sequence 2. The maneuver sequence number is always 1 for non-bifurcation maneuvers.
table.name: MNR_Maneuver_Arrow

table.description: Maneuver Path Index table identifies the network features involved in maneuvers (Road Element) in the order of occurrence within each maneuver. Sequence number 1 is always the network feature that is located before the maneuver decision point. Standard maneuvers contain 1 road element before the decision point. A Linear Assignment Maneuver and an Image Maneuver can have multiple road elements before the decision junction.
table.name: MNR_Maneuver_Path_Idx

table.description:
Network Geometry Link table contains the line geometry of the network features (Road Element, Address Area Boundary Element and Ferry Element) and the Railway Element. In case the geometry of multiple network features and/or the Railway Element is equal, there is only one Network Geometry Link record. Also in case of stacked network links or network links and Railway Element, the geometry is only stored once. This normalized geometry representation, allows making an improved display :
  • Stacked network features can be identified.
  • Road Elements that have a rail line can be identified.
table.name: MNR_Netw_Geo_Link

table.description: Restriction table contains the restriction information for network features (Road Element, Address Area Boundary Element and Ferry Element) and maneuvers. There is one record in the Restriction table for each single restriction (several kind of restrictions are not combined). Depending on the kind of restriction, the appropriate fields are populated. It is possible to have multiple restrictions for one feature. There will be a different sequence number for each restriction belonging to the same feature. The combination of feature ID and sequence number is the primary key for the Restriction table.
